In TypeScript, you can use Type Assertion to tell the type system "I know that in theory this value may have these multiple types, but in practice I know it will only have this one". Type assertion is like a type cast in other languages, but it doesn't perform any special checking or restructuring of data. It has no runtime impact and is used purely by the compiler.

Here is how you can do it:

```typescript
let someValue: any = "this is a string";

let strLength: number = (<string>someValue).length;
```

Or, you can use the "as" syntax:

```typescript
