To draw a chessboard in LaTeX using FEN notation, you can use the `chessboard` and `xskak` packages. Here is an example of how you can do it:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{xskak}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\newgame
\chessboard[setfen=8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1]

\end{document}
```

In the `setfen` command, you can replace `8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1` with your FEN notation. The FEN notation represents the game state: the position of each piece on the board, the player to move, the availability of castling, the target square of the last pawn to have moved two squares forward from its starting position (for en passant), the number of half-moves since the last pawn move or capture (for the fifty-move rule), and the number of full moves completed in the game.

For example, the FEN notation for the starting position of a chess game is `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1`.

So, if you want to draw the starting position of a chess game, you can do:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{xskak}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\newgame
\chessboard[setfen=rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1]

\end{document}
```

This will draw a chessboard with all the pieces in their starting positions.

